 United Kingdom","of, Caldwll, Worcester, England":"Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","Alston Hall, Worcester, Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","Toulon-sur-Allier, Allier, Auvergne, France":"Toulon-sur-Allier, Allier, Auvergne, France","Worceshire, Enland":"Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Alston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish:","from the Middle English personal name <i>Alstan</i>, which is a coalescence of several different Old English personal names: <i>Æthelstān</i> ‘noble stone’, <i>Ælfstān</i> ‘elf stone’, <i>Ealdstān</i> ‘old stone’, or <i>Ealhstān</i> ‘temple stone’.","habitational name from any of various places called Alston (in Cumbria, Lancashire, Devon, and Somerset) or Alstone (in Gloucestershire and Staffordshire). With the exception of Alston in Cumbria, which is formed with the Old Norse personal name <i>Halfdan</i>, these placenames all consist of an Old English personal name + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’, for example <i>Ælfsige</i> in the case of Alstone in Gloucestershire."],"variants":[{"name":"Aston","meanings":["English:","from the Middle English personal name <i>Ad(e)stan</i>, which is usually from Old English <i>Æthelstān</i> (see   Alston  ). It may also be from the much rarer Old English name <i>Ēadstān</i>.","habitational name from any of several places in England called Aston. Most were named with Old English <i>ēast</i> ‘east’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’. In a few cases the first element is <i>æsc</i> ‘ash tree’."]},{"name":"Allston","meanings":["English: variant of   Alston  ."]},{"name":"Hailstone","meanings":["habitational name from Hailstone Hill in Wiltshire or Hailstone Farm in Gloucestershire, the former of which may be derived from Old English <i>hālig-stān</i> ‘holy stone’ or <i>hagolstān</i> ‘hailstone’ (Middle English <i>hawelston</i>, <i>hailston</i>).","from <i>Ailstan</i>, a variant of the Old English personal name <i>Æthelstān</i> (‘noble’ + ‘stone’), with prosthetic initial <i>H-</i>. The first element of the Old English name developed from <i>Æthel-</i> to <i>Ægel-</i> and then to <i>Ail-</i>; it was often further shortened to <i>Al-</i> (see   Alston  ).","English:"]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice Alston was born in 1450, in Worcester, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Robert Alston and Joane Standolffe. She had at least 4 sons and 1 daughter with John Caldwell. She died in 1482, in Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 32."},"et":{"1450–1482":"1450–1482","1444–1482":"1444–1482","1460–1475":"1460–1475","1467–1535":"1467–1535","1475–Male":"1475–Surnud","1477–Male":"1477–Surnud","1479–1521":"1479–1521","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1482":"1482","abt 1475":"umbes 1475","abt 1477":"umbes 1477","abt 1467":"umbes 1467","1535":"1535","1479":"1479","1467":"1467","1521":"1521","1477":"1477","1444":"1444","1475":"1475","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, England","London, London, England":"Lond